<subSubSection pageId="84" pageNumber="85" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="84.[151,1436,1792,2033]" pageId="84" pageNumber="85">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,470,1792,1817]" pageId="84" pageNumber="85">Differential Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Habitus similar to that of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Perkins" authorityYear="2012" box="[789,923,1793,1817]" class="Insecta" family="Epimetopidae" genus="Epimetopus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="84" pageNumber="85" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="deceptus">
<emphasis box="[789,923,1793,1817]" italics="true" pageId="84" pageNumber="85">E. deceptus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[942,1053,1793,1817]" captionStart="FIGURE 113" captionStartId="75.[151,250,1726,1749]" captionTargetBox="[203,1397,213,1683]" captionTargetId="figure-154@75.[177,1411,193,1705]" captionTargetPageId="75" captionText="FIGURE 113. Epimetopus deceptus holotype, dorsal and lateral habitus, and perpendicular to pronotum." pageId="84" pageNumber="85">Figs. 113</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[1069,1114,1793,1817]" captionStart="FIGURE 119" captionStartId="82.[151,250,1994,2017]" captionTargetBox="[276,1322,509,1981]" captionTargetId="figure-169@82.[247,1339,489,2001]" captionTargetPageId="82" captionText="FIGURE 119. Epimetopus fimbriatus holotype, dorsal and lateral habitus, and perpendicular to pronotum." pageId="84" pageNumber="85">119</figureCitation>
); differing therefrom in the smaller and denser pronotal tubercles, the larger denticles on the anterior angles of the elytra, and the larger size (ca. 3.59 v. 
<quantity box="[287,394,1865,1889]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.73" pageId="84" pageNumber="85" unit="mm" value="2.73">2.73 mm</quantity>
). The aedeagi of the two species are marked dissimilar (
<figureCitation box="[1043,1151,1865,1889]" captionStart="FIGURE 114" captionStartId="76.[151,250,1833,1856]" captionText="FIGURE 114. Epimetopus deceptus, aedeagus of holotype." pageId="84" pageNumber="85">Figs. 114</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[1165,1211,1865,1889]" captionStart="FIGURES 120–123" captionStartId="83.[151,264,1697,1720]" captionTargetBox="[178,1410,182,1665]" captionTargetId="figure-93@83.[164,1424,169,1681]" captionTargetPageId="83" captionText="FIGURES 120–123. Epimetopus, aedeagi of holotypes. 120. E. tuberculatus. 121. E. venezuelensis. 122. E. fimbriatus. 123. E. tridens." pageId="84" pageNumber="85">122</figureCitation>
). The aedeagus can perhaps be compared with that of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Perkins" authorityYear="2012" box="[546,657,1901,1925]" class="Insecta" family="Epimetopidae" genus="Epimetopus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="84" pageNumber="85" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tridens">
<emphasis box="[546,657,1901,1925]" italics="true" pageId="84" pageNumber="85">E. tridens</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[675,775,1901,1925]" captionStart="FIGURES 120–123" captionStartId="83.[151,264,1697,1720]" captionTargetBox="[178,1410,182,1665]" captionTargetId="figure-93@83.[164,1424,169,1681]" captionTargetPageId="83" captionText="FIGURES 120–123. Epimetopus, aedeagi of holotypes. 120. E. tuberculatus. 121. E. venezuelensis. 122. E. fimbriatus. 123. E. tridens." pageId="84" pageNumber="85">Fig. 123</figureCitation>
); they have a similar general plan, but differ markedly in proportions. In 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Perkins" authorityYear="2012" box="[329,478,1937,1961]" class="Insecta" family="Epimetopidae" genus="Epimetopus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="84" pageNumber="85" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="fimbriatus">
<emphasis box="[329,478,1937,1961]" italics="true" pageId="84" pageNumber="85">E. fimbriatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
the median lobe is much wider, as are the parameres and the basal piece; also, the dorsal processes of the median lobe are located more proximally, and the basal piece is markedly more arcuate. The habitus of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Perkins" authorityYear="2012" box="[269,415,2009,2033]" class="Insecta" family="Epimetopidae" genus="Epimetopus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="84" pageNumber="85" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="fimbriatus">
<emphasis box="[269,415,2009,2033]" italics="true" pageId="84" pageNumber="85">E. fimbriatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Perkins" authorityYear="2012" box="[469,579,2009,2033]" class="Insecta" family="Epimetopidae" genus="Epimetopus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="84" pageNumber="85" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tridens">
<emphasis box="[469,579,2009,2033]" italics="true" pageId="84" pageNumber="85">E. tridens</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are markedly dissimilar (
<figureCitation box="[865,971,2009,2033]" captionStart="FIGURE 118" captionStartId="81.[151,250,1908,1931]" captionTargetBox="[177,1421,428,1887]" captionTargetId="figure-179@81.[151,1436,413,1893]" captionTargetPageId="81" captionText="FIGURE 118. Epimetopus tridens holotype, dorsal and lateral habitus, and perpendicular to pronotum." pageId="84" pageNumber="85">Figs. 118</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[983,1028,2009,2033]" captionStart="FIGURE 119" captionStartId="82.[151,250,1994,2017]" captionTargetBox="[276,1322,509,1981]" captionTargetId="figure-169@82.[247,1339,489,2001]" captionTargetPageId="82" captionText="FIGURE 119. Epimetopus fimbriatus holotype, dorsal and lateral habitus, and perpendicular to pronotum." pageId="84" pageNumber="85">119</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
